recalls.Summary: McLaren Automotive Incorporated (McLaren) is recalling certain 2016-2020 720S, 2019 Senna, 2020 GT, and 2017-2019 570GT vehicles.  The Noise, Vibration, and Harshness (NVH) foam pad underneath the fuel tank may retain moisture and corrode the fuel tank, potentially causing a fuel leak.
recalls.Consequence: A fuel leak in the presence of an ignition source increases the risk of a fire.
recalls.Remedy: McLaren will notify owners, and dealers will remove the NVH foam pad from the vehicle and inspect the fuel tank.  If the fuel tank is found to have corrosion, it will be replaced.  Repairs will be performed free of charge.  The recall began June 17, 2020.  Owners may contact McLaren's Client Services department at 855-202-8815, Monday to Friday between 9am and 6pm EST or customerservice.na@mclaren.com.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: Hydraulic Door Actuator Failure
issues.description: The hydraulic door actuators that control the McLaren's signature dihedral doors can fail, causing doors to open slowly, stick, or fail to open entirely. This is often due to hydraulic pump or actuator seal failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace hydraulic actuators, pump, or hydraulic lines. Often requires specialized McLaren diagnostic equipment.
issues.prevention: Regular hydraulic system maintenance, avoid forcing doors when they operate slowly

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Body Panel Delamination
issues.description: Carbon fiber body panels may develop delamination issues, particularly around high-stress areas like door frames and rear quarter panels. This can be caused by manufacturing defects or environmental exposure.
symptoms: Visible separation in carbon fiber layers
Bubbling or raised areas on panels
issues.fix_description: Panel replacement or professional carbon fiber repair. May require complete panel replacement for structural components.
issues.prevention: Avoid extreme temperature changes, proper storage, regular inspection of carbon fiber components

issues.title: Infotainment System Freezing and Crashing
issues.description: The IRIS infotainment system is prone to freezing, crashing, or becoming unresponsive. This affects navigation, climate control, and vehicle settings access.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, system reset, or complete infotainment module replacement in severe cases.
issues.prevention: Keep software updated, avoid using system during startup sequence

issues.title: Active Suspension Component Failure
issues.description: The Proactive Chassis Control II system can experience failures in dampers, height sensors, or control modules, leading to poor ride quality and handling issues.
symptoms: Vehicle sitting too low or high
issues.fix_description: Replace failed dampers, sensors, or control modules. Requires specialized McLaren diagnostic equipment and calibration.
issues.prevention: Avoid extreme driving conditions, regular suspension system inspection

issues.title: Engine Bay Fire Risk from Fuel Line Issues
issues.description: Some vehicles experienced fuel line failures in the engine bay, potentially leading to fuel leaks and fire risk. This prompted a recall for certain production batches.
symptoms: Fuel smell in cabin or near vehicle
Visible fuel leaks in engine bay
issues.fix_description: Recall repair involves fuel line replacement and inspection of surrounding components. Covered under warranty/recall.
issues.prevention: Immediate attention to any fuel odors, regular engine bay inspection

issues.title: Transmission Control Module Failure
issues.description: The dual-clutch transmission control module can fail, causing harsh shifting, transmission fault codes, or complete transmission failure in drive modes.
issues.fix_description: Replace transmission control module and update software. May require clutch calibration.
issues.prevention: Proper warm-up procedures, avoid aggressive driving when transmission is cold

issues.title: Air Conditioning Condenser Damage
issues.description: The A/C condenser is positioned in a vulnerable location and prone to damage from road debris, leading to refrigerant leaks and system failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace A/C condenser and recharge system. May require front bumper removal for access.
issues.prevention: Avoid debris on roadways, consider protective film installation

issues.title: Electronic Parking Brake Malfunction
issues.description: The electronic parking brake system can malfunction, either failing to engage or release properly, sometimes leaving the vehicle stranded.
issues.fix_description: Replace EPB actuators or control module. Requires system calibration and bleeding.
issues.prevention: Regular brake system maintenance, avoid forcing EPB when malfunctioning

issues.title: Hood Strut Failure and Alignment Issues
issues.description: The hood struts can fail or the hood can develop alignment issues, potentially causing the hood to not stay open properly or close incorrectly.
issues.fix_description: Replace hood struts and adjust hood alignment. May require body shop expertise for proper alignment.
issues.prevention: Support hood manually when struts seem weak, gentle hood operation

issues.title: Exhaust System Cracking and Heat Shield Issues
issues.description: The high-performance exhaust system can develop cracks in the pipes or heat shields, leading to exhaust leaks and potential heat damage to surrounding components.
issues.fix_description: Replace damaged exhaust sections or heat shields. May require custom fabrication for certain components.
issues.prevention: Avoid bottoming out, regular inspection of exhaust components

editorial.hero_blurb: The McLaren 720S represents the sweet spot of McLaren's lineup, delivering 710 horsepower in a package that's both devastatingly quick and surprisingly livable. This is supercar engineering at its finest, wrapped in dramatic dihedral doors and carbon fiber artistry.
editorial.essence: The 720S is McLaren's masterclass in balancing extreme performance with real-world usability. It's a car that can embarrass hypercars on track while remaining composed enough for daily driving, thanks to McLaren's obsession with aerodynamics and chassis sophistication.
editorial.heritage: Following the legendary McLaren F1 and the groundbreaking MP4-12C, the 720S launched in 2017 as part of McLaren's Super Series. It represents decades of Formula 1 expertise distilled into road car form, carrying forward McLaren's carbon fiber monocoque construction and active aerodynamics philosophy.
editorial.design_philosophy: Form follows function defines every curve of the 720S. The dramatic bodywork isn't just for show - every line serves aerodynamic purpose, from the eye sockets that channel air to the brake cooling ducts integrated into the dihedral doors. It's sculpture meets wind tunnel.
editorial.motorsport_history: While the 720S itself doesn't race, it's built on decades of McLaren F1 expertise and shares DNA with McLaren's track-focused models. The car's active aerodynamics and carbon fiber construction directly benefit from McLaren's ongoing Formula 1 program.
editorial.engine_character: The 4.0L twin-turbo V8 is a masterpiece of forced induction, delivering power with shocking immediacy yet remarkable refinement. Unlike older turbocharged engines, this unit responds instantly to throttle inputs, feeling almost naturally aspirated in its delivery while producing devastating torque.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 7-speed dual-clutch transmission is telepathic in its responses, delivering lightning-quick shifts in Track mode or imperceptibly smooth changes in Comfort. Paddle shifts are crisp and decisive, with rev-matching that's perfectly calibrated.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The adaptive dampers and anti-roll bars create a chassis that can transform from boulevard cruiser to track weapon instantly. The carbon fiber monocoque provides incredible rigidity while the sophisticated suspension keeps the car planted yet compliant over varying surfaces.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulically-assisted steering provides genuine feedback from the road surface with perfect weighting. It's quick enough for track work yet stable at highway speeds, offering the kind of communication that builds confidence at any speed.
editorial.brake_confidence: Carbon ceramic brakes provide immense stopping power with excellent pedal feel and fade resistance. The brakes are progressive and easy to modulate, inspiring confidence whether you're trail-braking into a corner or making an emergency stop.
editorial.sound_signature: The twin-turbo V8 produces a sophisticated soundtrack that ranges from a refined rumble at idle to an intoxicating howl under full acceleration. The exhaust note is more refined than raw, befitting McLaren's technical approach to performance.
editorial.ideal_owner: The perfect 720S owner appreciates technical excellence and wants a supercar they can actually use regularly. They value McLaren's engineering sophistication and don't mind the exclusivity that comes with the brand's limited dealer network.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking maximum drama or traditional supercar theater should look elsewhere. The 720S prioritizes capability over spectacle, which may disappoint buyers wanting more emotional engagement or those needing extensive luggage space.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for well-maintained examples with service records from authorized McLaren dealers. The 720S is remarkably reliable for a supercar, but McLaren's limited service network makes maintenance history crucial.
cons: Less emotional engagement than some rivals

SUBJECT: McLaren 720S (2017-2022), pristine showroom condition.

SETTING: Private collector's industrial warehouse garage. Brick warehouse with arched windows OR modern concrete gallery OR vintage factory with timber beams.

COMPOSITION: Front 3/4 hero angle showing front fascia and driver's side profile. Show COMPLETE car (all four wheels, both bumpers, full roofline). Camera at knee height.

LIGHTING: Golden hour sunlight streaming through large industrial windows. Warm color temperature. Cinematic depth.

TECHNICAL: Magazine-quality automotive photography. Photorealistic, no CGI look. No people, no text, no watermarks, no logos, no license plates.
